segments.text: this is may 31st 1900 and we're sitting in the office of the executive director of the former students association and getting ready to interview porter garner iii porter use your mic for a sentence how's that test one two
A little stronger, I think, based on location.
To begin with, to introduce yourself to anyone that might hear this tape or read the transcription, describe family background, where you grew up, where you went to high school.
Okay.

I grew up in Laredo, Texas, down on the Rio Grande border with a father who was a member of the class of 1945, a grandfather who had two degrees from the University of Texas, and a degree from Texas A&I University.
In fact, something I'm rather proud of, when Texas A&I was founded, my grandfather was the first in line to enroll.

and would have been recorded as the first student to enroll at Texas A&I if not for the gentleman in him whereupon there was a young lady behind him and he said ladies first and she is recorded as the first person to enroll at Texas A&I.
However,
As a footnote to that, she did recognize that Porter S. Garner Sr., at the time, was in fact the first person and allowed her to be enrolled first.
Tremendous academic influence on me as a young man.
Had two older sisters, both graduates of the University of Texas with multiple degrees.
Our grandfather, Porter S. Garner Sr., voracious reader,
often emphasized reading and often rewarded us with books, particularly for birthdays and other anniversaries.
So, a tremendous influence on my life, Haskell, from the standpoint of learning, gaining knowledge, being self-informed.
In addition to that, my father and mother were both college graduates and promoted the value of education from my earliest recollection.
My father came to Texas A&M in 1941, and Texas A&M had just won a national championship in football.
He was a pretty good athlete.
He went to World War II.

was injured in Germany, severely so, but came back to Laredo, married my mother, a graduate of the Our Lady of Lake College in San Antonio, and went to work in the insurance business, but ultimately was recruited by my mother's father to work in the food service industry in Nuevo Laredo, Mexico, at a place called the Cadillac Bar.
And I mention that only because
It had somewhat of an influence on me as I grew up.
My interests were like many young men.
I love to hunt, finish, fish, love the outdoors.
Was not a Sterling student in high school, but did graduate from Laredo-Nixon High School in 1975 with honors and top 15% of my class, what have you.

But in those formative years leading up to my graduation from high school, the Cadillac bar influenced me from the perspective of seeing a lot of those people who were not privileged in any shape or fashion.
It instilled in me an appreciation and a respect for all people, regardless of their status in life, their class, their upbringing, their education, or what have you.
It also, as a byproduct, gave me a tremendous leg up on my fellow students at Texas A&M in that I was fluent in Spanish by the age of 15.
In fact, I would say that quite possibly at age 15, I was more fluent in Spanish than I was in English.
But I made a big mistake in 1975 when I graduated from Laredo Nixon High School.
I took a placement test hoping to place out of Spanish, and I did, placed out of about 12 hours of Spanish.

and in retrospect after struggling through my sophomore year at A&M I could have sure used those grade points and credits I'll tell you so that was a mistake on my behalf but I'd just say that my background growing up on the border having an interest in in the outdoors
being raised around a restaurant and bar with predominantly Spanish-speaking employees was a real benefit to me in many, many ways.

And it served me well when I got to Texas A&M because it gave me a diversity and, more importantly, I think, an appreciation for all cultures that I would soon be thrown in with at Texas A&M that I had not been exposed to in Laredo.
Interestingly enough, I did not come to A&M as a freshman.
I was accepted to A&M as a freshman, but like many young men at age 17, I was in love, and I decided that Laredo Junior College might be a good stepping stone for me.
But that soon faded.
I made a trip to College Station in the fall of 1975 to see some friends who had in fact come to A&M.
And went to a midnight Yale practice with those friends and met a young lady and quickly fell out of love and reapplied for admission and came to A&M the fall of 1976 as a sophomore.
I would characterize my three and a half years at A&M as some of the best years of my life.
I'd say that much like you've probably heard in all of your, I suspect in all of your interviews with former students, made the best friends I've ever had, people that I consider lifelong friends.
I majored in business, specifically marketing.
Here, let us go through that.
I'm sorry, I was getting ahead of you.
When you had visited before, what were your early impressions of what the campus seemed to be like?
That's a great question, and I could go on for about two hours on that.
Being raised by a member of the class of 45, I was brought up to A&M in the 60s.
My earliest recollection is a class reunion, albeit I think what they call or referred to as an informal class reunion in the early 60s, when Texas A&M was not winning a whole lot of football games.
However,
That didn't stop the Class of 45 from coming to town and having a good time.
I do recall many late night parties discussing not only the football fortunes, but the future of the then football coach.
But in 1967, I was about 10 years old, we came to a football game on my birthday and Texas A&M won the game.
We went back to the Ramada Inn with a class of 45 traditionally gathered in a party room.
and there wasn't much discussion.
There wasn't much talk about the coach or the football team and the party was over about 1030.

That was a distinct impression on me as opposed to many previous trips where we had not won the game and the party went on till 2 and 3 in the morning with many discussions about you know how we were going to turn things around.

My impressions of A&M early on, Haskell, were such that it represented something I wanted to be a part of, something that I didn't really take advantage of in high school, and that was an involvement, an opportunity to participate, an encouragement to participate by students, faculty, staff, administrators, and quite frankly, maybe an expectation that when you came to A&M as a student,
you were expected to be involved and to contribute to the success of the university.
That was not my high school experience whatsoever.
So I saw that as a young man.
I witnessed it.
I came to A&M in the early 70s to see friends who had graduated prior to me, and my impressions of A&M were one of
an all-inclusive welcome atmosphere.
There wasn't a lot of who's who or where they're from or what their father did or what kind of car they drove, where they lived, what kind of clothes they wore.
It was just more welcome.
You're an Aggie now.
We're all Aggies.
Let's go get a hamburger or pizza.
That was a bigger impression on me than the academic reputation of the business school.
I think I could have gone to the University of Texas or Texas Tech where I had an opportunity to attend with some financial aid and probably had a similar academic experience.

in all honesty but the reason i came to a m was was distinctly because of the influence of my father and the impressions that i had over that nine or ten year period from 1966 to 1975. now you came as a transfer student correct were you a civilian or in the corps i was a civilian i i wanted to be in the corps to be honest with you

But having not come as a freshman, I had heard horror stories about frogging in, and therefore I lived in Moore Hall where some Laredo friends lived and just immediately got involved in the dorm life.
Describe living in a civilian dorm in those days.
Oh, it was great.
It was a great experience.
It was everything I expected.
It was everything I wanted it to be.
It was a lot of what I had witnessed in the early 70s, the camaraderie, the involvement, the total immersion into campus life.
I just can't imagine having a better experience at Texas A&M.
I am glad that I didn't take an opportunity to live rather cheaply, almost rent-free, off campus with some Laredo Aggies at the time.
It was a great experience for me, no doubt.
Describe how you academically got your courses.
What was the transfer system and registration and all that?
Well, let me go back in time and say that becoming a business major was not my decision.
With my background in the outdoors and involvement in the Future Farmers of America in high school and my love of agriculture, I actually had an interest in majoring in agriculture.
I had an FFA opportunity scholarship.
I had a public speaking scholarship.
All of this was basically to major in agriculture.
and at Texas A&M in one particular scholarship.
And my father talked to me very seriously about my background and said, you know, you've got a pretty good background in ranching and the outdoors.
Why don't you major in business?
And then if you really want to ranch or have a significant interest in coming back to ranch or something, get you a master's in agriculture.
But why don't you start off in business?
And I'm glad he talked me into that because I came to A&M and got into the marketing department and absolutely loved that.
It fit my background.
The transfer aspect was somewhat paved for me by a fellow named Ed Cooper.
At the time, I believe his title was Dean of Admissions, and we no longer have a Dean of Admissions per se.
Ed Cooper was a family friend, had come to Laredo on several hunting trips and shopping sprees and tying back to the Cadillac bar.

I do not recall this, however, Ed Cooper has told me on many occasions that his first introduction to me as a young boy was seeing me cleaning out spittoons and sweeping and polishing the bar rail at the Cadillac bar and witnessing firsthand what he called my industrious, hardworking nature.
So he was quite a champion of mine in my process to transfer to A&M and made it rather easy for me.
And I just don't recall any real challenges to getting into Texas A&M.
And so you started off as a business major.
Correct.
Describe your reaction to classes that first semester.
That was a bit of an eye-opener.
Although I graduated from a large high school, graduated with almost 600 in my class in 1975, I'd never attended a class with 300 people in it.
So to walk into a accounting 229 class in a theater style setting with a stage and a microphone and speaker system and a slide screen with 250 people in it was a bit intimidating to me.
I consequently used that as a pretty good excuse to
to not do well in the class, and in fact took 229 again.

Made a D in it my first semester at A&M, but took it again and made a B and then flourished in accounting 230 and so on, but a lot of my first recollections of classes were relative to the level of competition I was now up against.
not necessarily to the demanding nature of the subject matter.
The reading or the actual material in the text was not intimidating to me.
What was intimidating to me was all of a sudden being thrown in with kids who were all more aggressive, smarter, harder working, and had better study habits than I had.
Did it matter as a civilian student that you were a transfer?
No, sir.
If it did, I was never made aware of it.
And how did you, as a transfer, get accustomed and acquainted with all kinds of Aggie traditions?
Well, that goes back probably to my upbringing once again.
You know, with my dad being a member of the class of 45, a rather proud class at Texas A&M, I was introduced to traditions early on.
In fact, as a freshman in high school,

I remember keeping a log of activities at A&M that I witnessed either in trips with my father or reading the newspaper, used to follow sports scores, used to follow any headline that involved Texas A&M.
And I kept somewhat of an Aggie diary.

knowing that I wanted to probably go to A&M and hope to be accepted, so I actually had a bit of a scrapbook regarding A&M, its traditions, any changes that were ongoing, construction, things that I could predict that I might enjoy when I got there in the fall of 75, which subsequently I did not, but looked at a lot of things in terms of anticipation.
So I was introduced to
A lot of history and traditions early on.
That first semester, as you look back on it, were there any counselors and or teachers that were important to your life that first semester or first year?
Some by default.
I was majoring in marketing, as I said.
The head of the department was a fellow named Sam Gillespie.
And I had not done real well my first fall semester at A&M.
Accounting 229 was a major reason for that.
And went to see Sam Gillespie at his request at the end of the semester.
And was lectured somewhat about my dedication to my studies.
and tried to do a little better in the spring and got a letter from Sam telling me that I was not necessarily A&M material.
So I went to see him and he was not encouraging and tried to tell me that that I would be better served by maybe returning to Laredo Junior College.
In retrospect, that was maybe a good conversation for me because it pointed me down the hall to a man named Herb Thompson.
And Herb was the antithesis of Sam Gillespie.
Herb was encouraging.
Herb saw value in my experiences and treated me like the 18-year-old that I was and simply talked to me in terms of what I really wanted out of this experience at A&M and did I want a degree.

from college and how would I use that and did I want to be a marketing major and just spoke to me in a very mature way but a very conversational way not as a professor of marketing so to speak but as a friend who wanted to see me succeed.
I would be pleased and just quite frankly elated to go on record as crediting Herb Thompson with a lot of the influence, positive influence, in my academic career at A&M.
Now did you and your buddies pick up, were there still nicknames for faculty members?
Share some of those you recall.
Well, I'm trying to think of some of the ones that I probably ought to be on record with here.
Did Herb Thompson have one?
No, he didn't.
I don't remember one.
No, if he did, I don't.
And Sam is too recent.
He didn't get one, I don't think.
Now, we had some ugly names for some of those guys, but...
Dr. Dan the Great Point Man was still here, and he was one of my favorites.
Judge Stewart was teaching business law, and the judge was a guy that everybody tried to sign up for.
And I don't, you know, really until the end of semester, I don't know that I could have told you what his first or last name was.
All I knew was during registration in the summer of 1977,

it was emphatic that you sign up for the judges course and uh and i did and that was a great course for me business law 312 and uh and what what made it such an important course he uh held up the book on the first day of class and said has anybody bought the book and i think four or five people had bought it by that first day i being one of those and he said well that's nice he said would y'all be willing to share that with the rest of the class on occasion
And I nodded my head, and he said, because I'm going to talk a lot.
And he said, you're going to learn more from me than you'll ever learn from reading that book.
And while that might have seemed a little arrogant at the time, it was prophecy.
It was accurate.
And it was indeed the most engaging class I probably had at A&M.
He made business law as interesting as you can in terms of real-life experiences.
And while most of his tests related to text material, it had practical, real-life applications.
And so that's what I recall about that class.
Describe the routine of a typical day of classes for you and your buddies.
What time did y'all get up and what did you do when?
I was probably a throwback maybe in many ways.
I scheduled as many classes as I could early in the morning.
Having that agricultural upbringing,
I wanted the balance of my day to be available for what I needed to get done.
I sought every 8 o'clock, 9 o'clock, 10 o'clock class I could.
And most of my mornings were filled with classes.
And the MSC was a very popular venue for social or academic opportunities, whatever.
That was kind of the midday gathering place, the watering hole, if you will.
And it was not only a place where my buddies went.
but it was probably the one universal opportunity during a weekday to meet a young lady or to have an excuse to study with the young lady.
And there was no other, other than maybe Sabisa Hall for lunch, a common ground to socialize and at the same time benefit your academic pursuits.
The afternoons, I hate to admit this on the record, but were usually spent back at the dorm in bull sessions or watching TV or just hanging out as we used to do.
And athletics was a big part of my life and intramurals therein played a big part and that was usually a late afternoon activity.
And then it was usually something at Sabisa by 5 30 or 6.
That was a big routine.
And that was another social opportunity because while you might go over and eat within the span of 20 or 30 or 45 minutes at the most, Sabisa was an hour or hour and a half experience.
And it was usually relative to something other than eating.
It was the challenges of
getting the certain food you wanted back to the dorm, or the silverware you needed to complete your set, or the tray that you needed, or the glass that you didn't have for your toothbrush.
So there were other things that Sabise offered as a side note.
That was kind of the day.
And then if I did some really hard line studying, it was usually in the late hours, 8 o'clock, 9 o'clock.
In the dining hall, did you civilian students use Aggie slang for the food?
Oh, yes.
Oh, yeah.
Oh, yeah.
We picked up on a lot of the old core terminology.
And, you know, shoot the blood was a common phrase you heard when you needed the ketchup, or a deal, which was a piece of bread.
What were, as you recall, what were some of your favorite mess hall, dining hall foods?
Shoot the blood was one of my all-time favorites.
Pass the dirt, which was the pepper.
Well, but then I'm talking about the dishes.
Oh.
Well, you know, coming from Laredo, I was starved for Mexican food.
There was no Mexican food, in my opinion, in Cebisa Dining Hall.
My buddies used to kind of anticipate my concoctions because I would introduce them to things that, quite frankly, this region of the country had not seen yet, such as fajitas.
Dr. Frank Litter's class of 43 got to know me through Ed Cooper,
and had me out to his house in the fall of 1976 because he heard that I could do something with a skirt steak that he'd never seen as an animal science professor in all his days.
I didn't regard it as any big deal.
I simply showed up one weekend coming back from Laredo on a Sunday night with what we called a fajita and

soaked it in some Italian dressing and threw it on a barbecue pit and I brought some flour tortillas back from Laredo and some avocados and some onions and I was hailed as you know quite the chef for that experience and so my buddies picked up on that and of course fajitas are revolutionary now but
Back in 1976, that was a real treat to these people.
It was $1.89 a pound butcher's cut of meat.
And so going back to Sabeza, there were times when people would ask me, what are you going to do with the tortilla today?
I'd go over and slap something in it and introduce them to what is now, I guess, known as a burrito or a breakfast taco.
They'd never seen scrambled eggs put in a tortilla with hot sauce.
And so while that was very common to me, it was interesting to see the faces of people who were trying something for the first time.
Now did you and your buddies play games in the dining hall?
Oh, a few.
We had one, I guess,
There's a known food fight that is memorable to me prior to a home game on a Friday night.
And I don't know that that's continued, but the Friday night prior to a home football game
was often the rowdiest night of the week in Sebesa Dining Hall and much anticipated.
That was the one day of the week where at 5.30 or 5.15, I think as I recall, when the doors opened to Sebesa,
There, in fact, was a line to get in.
It might have had something to do with the fact that you might have had a date on Friday night before a home football game, and that involved a 7 or 8 o'clock time.
But for the most part, male, female, Sabisa was a tremendous party on Friday nights.
And yes, there were food fights, and yes, there were games, and a lot of activity up until 7.30 when the dining hall closed.
What was the typical dress, apparel, for a young man and civilian student in those days?
Oh, I hate to admit this to you, Haskell, but too many tight clothes.
Too many tight clothes.
Too much influence, I guess, from Saturday Night Fever, which came out, I think, in 1976.
Bell-bottoms, t-shirt.
I wore boots quite a bit.
In fact, as an interesting side note to this interview, my first college roommate in Moore Hall at Texas A&M was matched up with me by virtue of my boots.
I got to Moore Hall the first day students could move in on a Tuesday afternoon, drove up from Laredo, checked in.
I bet there weren't five students in the whole dorm, including the resident advisors.
And got very well situated, which is my nature.
And by Wednesday or Thursday, I was touring the campus and getting my feel for what I was going to be doing when classes started.
And on Friday, I was expecting a roommate to show up.
I don't recall his name.
Thompson, I think, was his last name, and he never showed up.
On Sunday evening, I had two young freshmen knock on my door, and they were made aware that I did not have a roommate.
And as a transfer student, not only do I not have a roommate, but I'm on the first floor in a corner room.
Hmm.
which was a coveted, coveted situation.
And surprising to me, as was detailed to me, that a senior hadn't already taken that over.
But these two young freshmen knock on my door, and they are not roommates.
However, they want to be roommates.
And they detail for me that they have an option for me.

that they are living on the fourth floor, and one of them has a roommate who is willing to move out, and they thought he would be a good match for me because they had seen me walking down the hall with a pair of wingtip boots, and they said, he wears the same boots you do.

and y'all must get along y'all must have similar backgrounds he has a deer mount in his room and you have a deer mount in your room so i agreed to visit with him and see what went on and uh turns out his name was vance mitchell he was a sophomore as i was from edna texas and we became immediate friends and we lived together for the better part of a year and a half until he moved out into an apartment
But I thought that was an interesting story.
Describe what was  how was that room furnished?
What was in that room?
Oh, the typical bunks that you could dismantle and arrange.
But my next roommate came along.
His name was Kevin Baker, and he was in the class of 80.
And he and I had this wild idea to build a very popular
bed at the time that was popular around campus known as a loft and we built a loft allowing us to bring a couch into the room and set up the room in a
